<div class="non_toggle_area" id="comment-4256795">
  <div class="non_toggle_label">
       <span class="scomments_info">Wed, 12/18/2013 - 09:54 | <a href="/news/2013-12-18/bitcoin-crashes-after-china-bans-new-btc-deposits-pboc-gets-ddosed-retaliation#comment-4256795" class="active">4256795</a></span>
              <b><a href="/users/pt" title="View user profile.">PT</a></b>
  </div>

  <div class="comment-content">
    <div class="author"><div class="picture">
  <a href="/users/pt" title="View user profile."><img src="/sites/all/themes/newsflash/images/bagicon.png" alt="PT&#039;s picture" title="PT&#039;s picture"  /></a></div>
</div><div class="author"></div>
    <p>Can you get tulips for free or do they cost money now? &nbsp;50 cents? &nbsp;2 dollars? &nbsp;Tulips might have hit zero for a while but then they then reverted to their true value. &nbsp;And there was never a limit of 21 million tulips. &nbsp;What is the true value of bitcoin? &nbsp;If it is flawed, then zero. &nbsp;If not, who knows?</p>
<p>So the Chinese govt banned bitcoin. &nbsp;Boo hoo hoo. &nbsp;Did prohibition stop alcohol? &nbsp;Did all the law enforcers stop using alcohol when it was banned? &nbsp;Given the short history of bitcoin, I won't believe that it is dead until its value has been exactly zero for a year or two. After all, what does that graph look like when extended back over the last 12 months?</p>
<p>Disclaimer: &nbsp;I don't think bitcoin is your average tulip but the truth is, I really don't have a clue. &nbsp;Feel free to enlighten us.</p>

